  "chunk_index": 24,
  "summary": "Inspector Hueish continues his investigation by questioning Mr. Aggles regarding his son Jacques's behavior. Mr. Aggles explains that he and his wife had decided to stop bailing Jacques out of trouble, which led to a confrontation where Jacques left the house angrily while threatening to return for money. Mr. Aggles admits he was shocked to learn Jacques was a murder suspect but noted he did not fear an attack. He also mentions he may have heard a doorbell ring after his wife left the room, though he is uncertain. Additionally, Mr. Aggles reveals he was unaware that Jacques had married until Jacques's wife arrived the following day.\n\nGwendolyn Vaughn, a typist, provides her account of the evening. She confirms that Mrs. Aggles left the room around 6:53 PM and notes that she herself left the house at 7:15 PM. Gwendolyn observes that the sitting room door was ajar as she left, though she did not enter to say goodnight. On her walk home toward Red Lane, she recalls a car splashing mud on her at an intersection.\n\nHester Aggles is also questioned about her movements. She states she left the house around 7:00 PM to attend a play at the Dreymouth Theatre. She explains that she went to her mother's room to ask for money for gasoline; while she initially suggests Mrs. Corsden gave her the money, she clarifies that she actually took money from Coulston after Mrs. Aggles instructed her to do so. Hester notes her last interaction with her mother involved saying goodnight while her mother sat at her desk. Corston Lindström corroborates Hester's timeline, stating she saw Hester driving toward the main road while walking toward the village.",
